name: Barney's NY Shopping for Luxury Skin Care
objective:
The objective of this study is to deeply understand how male and female luxury consumers choose their skin care regimens, and what influences their purchase choices. We'll look at the role of advertising and branding, as well as the shopping dynamics in department stores, boutiques, multi brand environments such as Sephora and online sources.

INFLUENCES:

- Song of Style (Maddie)

- highly specialized stores (Violet Grey, Maddie)

- word of mouth (everyone)

- sales rep at Neiman's (Laurie)

- print mags (Laurie, Joey Jagod)

- Korean skincare (Jillian, Janice, Jessica)

- their moms (Jillian, Janice, Geneveive)

 

STRONG LOYALTY TO A LINE:

Amore Pacific (Lauren)

La Mer (Christopher)

Clinique (Jillian, Genevieve)

Shishedo (Janice)

 

PROMISCUITY:

Many use vastly different lines - mix it up completely (Joey, Christopher)

 

EXCLUSIVE PRODUCT

- No appeal (Maddie) - better when a product is widely used and accepted

- "I don't really care that much about where products are sold. It doesn't say less about the brand in my opinion if it is sold at Ulta or Sephora." (Jillian)

- Joey - it makes a product feel special

 

GREAT COMMENTS ON LOVE OF TRYING NEW PRODUCTS

- Christopher

- Jillian

 

IMPORTANCE OF SAMPLING

- Diana loves getting samples at Sephora

- Laurie has made many purchases after getting samples of items with purchase

- Jillian: "I like the freebies because a lot of times that's how I find out about new products. For things like masks I am always trying new things so I love samples of those."

- Joey Jagod is more likely to shop at a store that offers free samples "I like to try things out before I commit to purchasing them especially if it's super expensive."

 

PRINT MAGS

- Laurie - old school Town & Country and Vogue - influed by Kate Blanchett ad for SK II

- Joey Jagod - GQ, Town & Country, and Vogue

- Merriman - Elle

- Farren 

- Jessica - Porter, Brit and American Vogue, W, Elle, T magazine from NY Times, Town & Country

name: Deutsch - Cetaphil Skincare
objective:
The objective of this study is to understand the sources of loyalty for Cetaphil brand skin care products amongst Regular Users, and to explore what obstacles may stand in the way amongst "Non Users" - ie regular users of competitive brands. We will seek to understand their daily skin care regimens, follow them while shopping for skin care products and listen to how they describe the potential benefits of Cetaphil and what (if anything) makes it unique and relevant.

SOME INITIAL HYPOTHESES:

- Does Cetaphil make women feel more in control of their skin?  Users seem to say so

- Does the simplicity of Cetaphil appeal to women?  It is super uncomplicated and doesn't try too hard

 

 

 

PREVENT OR FIX?

 - Ashley - Since I already have a skin condition, I want a cleanser and a moisture that fixes problems. ... I have had eczema for 6 years now. It's been a challenge to have healthy, normal looking skin. ... When I was younger I used to be very interested in new and trendy products. But now i have to be cautious of the products I use on my skin.

- Jessica - combatting acne.  She wants to feel like she can leave the house with no makeup on and feel good

 - Jodie - Prevention all the way for me I like light moisture that has a big punch leaving me feel hydrated but not oily.

 

AMONGST CETAPHIL FANS: - a few seem to use the moisturizing creme on multiple parts of body

Stephanie uses the moisturizer on face as well as parts of her body 

Emily M uses it on lips as well as face 

Others would use it all over but it's too expensive as an all-body solution.

Scent doesn't seem as important as it is to non-users (like Jodie)

  

WOMEN WHO DESCRIBE THEMSELVES AS HAVING SENSITIVE SKIN (Let's list them all):

Jodie (non-user), Jenean (when allergies flare up), Kristi (user)

 

AVEENO - people love it who have allergic reactions - swear by the ability to avoid or calm itchiness (Tal)

  

CETAPHIL OPPORTUNITIES:

The aveeno is what I bring traveling, but if I could find a travel size of cetaphil I would use that instead! Actually, I would use cetaphil on my body too but it's a bit more expensive so I reserve that for just my face. It's by far my favorite and I've been using it for as long as I can remember! I use it to remove my makeup and then put it all over my face after washing it. I also slather it on my lips in the winter and never need chapstick! - Emily M

name: Harper's BAZAAR Study
objective:
The objective of this study is to bring to life the female HENRY (High Earner Not Rich Yet) in America today. We will be exploring her lifestyle, her ideas about brands, her shopping behavior, her attitudes about luxury, her priorities in life and how those affect her spending, and the things to which she aspires.

ROLE MODELS:

Carole Radziwell, who always dresses young and looks fabulous. (Alison)

Michelle Obama! A strong woman who cares about the planet and what our children put in their mouths . And she loves fashion!!!! (Lynn)

Bethenny Frankel - an entrepreneur and Sheryl Sandberg- so emotionally strong (Kristen)

Sheryl Sandberg - as a women in business I love how she pushes and advocates for women's leadership. (Alexandra)

I admire young entrepreneurs like Emily Weiss and Tyler Haney. (Lauren)

"a combination of strong, entrepreneurial women who are creative and making a valuable contribution. Outspoken and no fear!" (Ivy)

"My mom because she loves my sisters and I so much and it makes me look forward to being a mom one day." (Aleks) 

"Oprah because of where she came from and how she did it all as a single women, her human rights role and her all around philanthropy" (Jeannie)

"My past boss is someone I look up to tremendously! She's a Harvard grad, twice--married with kids, very successful and has it all! So I know it's attainable." Also noted fashion bloggers/IG Models @ChiaraFerragni, @GaryPepper, and @SomethingNavy (Polina)

I think I have a lot of inspiring role models but they relate to different parts of my life for example my career woman/innovator vs fashion vs mom. I would say for innovation it is someone who is not well known in the U.S. Her name is Tu YouYou. She is a Nobel Laureate for her contribution to science by finding a treatment for malaria in the life 60s. She was a female leader in science in a communist society and also volunteered to be the first test subject to try the treatment. Despite not being in the medical field, I find her innovation and ability to think creatively about treatment inspiring and really showcasing the ability of smart women especially given the environment of China in the 60s. From a fashion perceptive I think Blake Lively and Kerry Washington pretty inspirational from a fashion sense. (Denelle)

"I'm really creating and living a lifstyle based on my own narrative." (Paige, on not having a role model)

My nana (she actually passed in the last year) but she is actually the definition of luxury, confidence, strength, independence, and individuality. (Jessica)

Chelsea Handler, Tina Fey, Amy Poehler (Melanie)

Sofia Coppola - we both love sneakers, tomboy and french inspired style, and minimal beauty) (Sylvia)

A couple role models of mine are Emma Watson, Kate Middleton, Beyoncé, Gisele, Amal Clooney because they are successful and established women that have a strong sense of identity, femininity and fashion. My mom is also a role model of mine for how to balance a personal family life and a professional one. (Jillian)

DEFINITION OF LUXURY:

"My personal definition of luxury is detailed perfection. Louis Vuitton is an example. The patterns match perfectly at the seam, the stitching is immaculate and there is a built in trust that you are buying what you expect from the brand. Replicas are easy to spot." (Nicole, displaying her LV handbag)

My personal definition of luxury is: - Exclusiveness - Craftmanship - Uniqueness - Exploration - a chance to experience (Paige)

"My personal definition of success is accomplishing the goals I set for myself. Here's a pic of my vision board. Put it out there to the universe and it will happen." (Nicole) 

"In my opinion, success has very little to do with money & power. Success is a multifaceted personal concept, I believe being successful means having a balance of happiness across several areas of life. For example: - Business - Relationships - Emotions - Impact on society - Giving" (PAIGE)

Slightly unreachable in terms of cost. So not something I would buy everyday - a treat (Kristen)

My personal definition of luxury - experience, ability to adventure, explore new places, being able to be in a place and in an outfit that is "picture perfect" (Jessica)

Luxury to me is in the eye of the beholder! For me that means the feel, buttery soft leather and design and craftsmanship. (Lynn)

LUXURY ITEMS COVETED:

International travel (Alexandra, Aleks, Alison)

Unusual items.  Can't be "basic" (is normcore dead?)  Alison:"The Fat Jewish posted a picture of my gold Michael Kors watch and said "how to know if you're a basic bitch." Ack! So now I gotta get rid of it."

Time to myself to reflect (Aleks)

Cartier + Chanel luxury items + BMW Car (Polina)

 

DEFINITION OF SUCCESS:

Time to help others (Aleks)

"My personal definition of success is... being able to take long trips. Like to Bora Bora. And do it right. 5 stars all the way." (Alison) 

Being able to buy a home (Denelle)

Being able to purchase luxury items without a credit card (Polina)

My personal definition of success is enjoying small luxuries like my favorite Starbucks. (Kristen)

My personal definition of success is contentment and balance in life. I will feel successful when I feel content and balanced with my job, my family, my friends. This picture is from the Sahara desert and was one of the most blissful moments of my life when I felt completely content. (Jillian)

I'm an immigrant and we literally came to this country in 1987 with nothing, so to be able to buy certain things was only a dream when I was younger. And now I have the financial freedom to do that-- its huge!  (Polina)

"My phone, money & passport definitely represent my definition of luxury. My phone allows me to organize and plan my life, my passport enables me to explore and clear my mind, and of course money supports my wild cravings!" (Paige)

My personal definition of success is....recognition. When I reach the level where people consider me one of the best for a skill or industry expert, that's when I know I've succeeded. I'm asked to speak at conferences or on panels, I'm interviewed for magazines/sites, I'm awarded for achievement....that's success to me. (Sylvia)

 

IMPORTANCE OF LOYALTY PROGRAMS:

Alison (Nordstrom)

Denelle (Nordsrom)

Alexandra (Bloomies)

Polina Loves the points, definitely important (Bloomies) 

Sylvia-Not a motivator, but a nice perk (SEPHORA) 

 

THESE GIRLS ARE ALL ABOUT CONTEMPORARY BRANDS - WITH SOME LUXURY MIXED IN:

Veronica Beard, Carven, Iro (Ivy)

name: Lululemon Global Brand Study 2018
objective:
The goal of this study is to reveal insights about athleisure enthusiasts, and what makes Lululemon fans ("Guests") distinct from other athleisure buyers. What are the drivers of brand loyalty? Who are the Enthusiasts and what is it about the brand that resonates with them? What obstacles stand in the way of loyalty? We'll talk to both Current Guests and "Potential Guests" (those who buy the brand occasionally or are lapsed buyers) as well as Educators (those who work at retail).

MODERATORS - are you hearing that there are two uses for athleisure - 1) serious working out (2) running around town/casually being with friends - and that people are sometimes buying different brands for those two types of occasions? - Malinda

Yes, I would agree with that. Is anyone hearing of brands who have clothing that fill both of those functions?? Adidas and LLL were voiced by my participants as being reliable workout gear but also cute and classic/modern style athleisure - for adidas this may have more to do with shoes, as their adidas originals are popular as a fashion sneaker. So far I've heard that Nike and Underarmor are two that are definitely viewed as serious workout gear, and Pink, Gap, Lulu tend to be more for athleisure/yoga workouts, or for around town. 

Adidas is a common denominator among my participants ages 18-24, with 4 out of 5 of them naming adidas in their top 3 favorite athleisure brands.     ~ Man

One of my participants will wear Lulu when going out. She feels it can lend itself to look a little dressier that other brands. She is also into retro Adidas. Another is somewhat of an athlete and seems less fashion consious, but more active than athleisure. The clothing is part of her active life and she wears Athleta, Under Armor, Patagonai, Adidas and Nike. - Steph

I'm hearing that LLL is a brand that can satisfy both functions - athleisure and leisure. One of my men (Geoffrey) thinks so too. - Ali

...and what about LOUNGEWEAR?!  One is Monroe on Bandier.com - steph

ON THE PURCHASE JOURNEY:

- Janessa Suarez (age 24), post 3 - influence of Snapchat, Kardashians

- Geoffrey does most of his athleisure purchasing on Instagram!

name: Veronica Beard & Loyalty
objective:
The objective of this study is to bring to life the current Veronica Beard customer - both current and potential. We want to understand her current shopping behavior and preferences, with a particular focus on sources of loyalty to apparel brands. Among Enthusiasts, we want to get a crystal clear picture of the unique role that Veronica Beard plays in her wardrobe and why she loves it. Among Potential customers, we want to identify the "ways in" that can help the brand win her interest and loyalty.

CURATION

Strong theme.  Everyone is looking for it, and it manifests in diff ways.  Some go to multibrand boutiques for it (Domenica), other use IG as a filter for a store's website (they post top sellers or outfits - Dorsa), look at the library on a site (Brittany B with the Outnet) or rely on a stylist (Natalie C, at NM)

CRITERIA FOR A SUPERSTAR PIECE

Versatility and she feels amazing in it

THE UNIFORM

Work to evening, athleisure, date night/out, special occasions, big client meetings... and just general basic/cute and casual are the occasions I'm hearing consistently.  Work to evening seems most frequent occasion?  But many of these women have creative-leaning, flexible jobs - a lot of blurred lines

THE BLAZER IS THE ICONIC ITEM

Not necessarily the dickey although she also famous for that

THE MEGHAN MARKLE EFFECT

Six women have mentioned her so far - Brittney, Natalie C, Caryn & Jennifer D (photo of their VB woman), and Elizabeth P (photo), Mona 

A LOT OF PLAYBACK OF EXPOSURE TO THE BRAND ON GOOP

CREATIVITY/EDGE

Seems to be the special sauce (Ivy, for one, but a few have mentioned) - let's listen specifically for this

SUBSCRIPTION

Maybe because the VB woman considers herself creative she is not going for this idea - none of my people anyway!  Anyone hearing something diff?

One of mine (Candance) liked the idea of stitchfix - but only if she could receive multiple brands....she definitely didn't want to be limited to a single brand. -Mandy

Two of mine liked the idea of a Veronica Beard subscription! (Jennifer D and Jessica B)

name: Hot Sox Fashion & Novelty Socks
objective:
Hot Sox is rebranding itself to spur growth and make its brand more distinct in a saturated marketplace. The goal of this study is to gather critical intelligence from potential customers to reveal what role socks play in their wardrobe, how they wear socks, how they discover new sock brands, trends, and looks, how they shop in general and how they shop for socks, their thoughts on gifting and receiving socks, and their feedback on the Hot Sox brand.

WHAT'S GOING ON WITH SOCKS?

 

Brian L - he's seeing Millennials in his office wearing colorful socks and he is inspired to do it too

 

Jeanne F - seeing more socks called out in fashion mags

 

Natalie F - seeing the sock trend on Instagram and on bloggers, wants to be a part of it

 

Kari P -  Seen lots of novelty socks popping up in stores and specialty sock stores popping up. Knows one trend of grooms giving their groomsmen fun novelty socks to wear on their wedding day

 

CAN THE HOT SOX BRAND SUSTAIN NOVELTY & FASHION??

 

Bryan W - it would be hard to survive without offering both a true fashion sock and novelty sock

 

Katherine L - could have different subsets under the brand like Hot Sox Sports, Hot Sox weekend, etc.

 

Natalie F - they could become more fashion while keeping some of their original prints

 

Robin Z - Hot Sox sounds novelty but they could have a fashion collection under a new name - would need to rebrand for fashion

 

CROSSOVER BETWEEN FASHION AND NOVELTY

 

Paula C - can definitely be an overlap, has socks that say “antisocial club” on them but also has stripes which makes them fashionable

 

Some feel novelty socks are fashionable - Stacy, Sabrina, Tal

 

MOST PEOPLE ARE EMBARRASSED OF HOW THEY STORE THEIR SOCKS

 

Seen mostly in videos like Sabrina and Kevin, Ross

 

BRANDS MATTER FOR PERFORMANCE SOCKS BUT NOT AS MUCH FOR NOVELTY OR FASHION (EXCEPTION IS DESIGNER SOCKS, EG JEANNIE, PAULA, NATALIE)

Ross with his lulu socks, Kevin with his TuffStuff socks, pretty much everyone with Nike for working out

 

SOCK ARE AN IMPULSE PURCHASE

Natalie F, Roig, Sabrina, Paula, Tal, Susu

 

SOCKS AS AN AFFORDABLE WAY TO DRESS UP AN OUTFIT

Natalie F - was looking for a way to spice up her style without buying new pieces so got into socks and it totally transformed her outfits

 

Stacy - dresses plainly at work (scrubs) so uses socks to bring color and personality to her outfits, wears a uniform so socks are the only way she can express herself

 

INSPIRATION - INSTAGRAM DRIVEN

Roig - purchased a pair of Stance socks from a Stance IG ad

 

MEET THE NOVELTY SOCK BUYER

Amanda, Susu, Ross

 

MEET THE FASHION SOCK BUYER

Jeannie, Tal

 

MEN AND SOCKS

 

Natalie F - guys have a lot of flexibility in socks because they wear dress shoes so often, can enhance a guys outfit [post 20]

 

SPORT NOVELTY

Big opportunity - eg Brian L, Amanda, Roig

 

EXECUTIONAL IDEAS

 

Pop up sock stores? - Natalie F

 

Matching yoga pants & socks - Paula

 

Kids novelty socks - big opportunity

 

High quality novelty - most are cheap! (eg Amanda)

 

Matching parent/child socks - Roig

 

Cooling/breathable fabric for performance socks - Roig and Sabrina

 

School spirit socks - college alma mater (eg Amanda, Brian W)

 

Adding a logo to sox (Bryan W and Natalie F with the “showy” comment)

 

Create a fusion category - high quality socks with funny themes (all other novelty are known as cheap quality thus tacky)

 

Novelty ankle socks - Roig

 

Glitter!!!! In novelty AND fashion socks - Paula, Stacy

 

Embellishments - Tal

 

Textures - Susu

 

I think Hot Sox should do similar gift box sets of sock patterns that can be worn interchangeably with each other! (susu)

 

I don't have any socks for my religion. if.i could find them I would wear.them (stacey)

 

would love matching socks. or even socks for kids and their dolls (stacey)

 

Pedi socks with tread to wear with slides (before yoga) (mallory)

 

Avoiding cankles (angled pedis?) (Mallory)

 

Anya hindmarch effect? (Paula, Kevin)

THEY LIKE TO ENJOY THEMSELVES AND MAKE FULL USE OF THEIR BREAKS

Jonathan - pool, foosball, arcade machine, ping pong

 

They look forward to breaks above all else (Jonathan, Kevin)

 

Best part of her job is that she can read on downtime, wants a public bookshelf - Nicole

 

Wants a gaming room - Nicole

 

MOST HAVE WORKED FOR THEIR COMPANY FOR YEARS

5 yrs - Kenyatta

 

13 yrs - Mike (but coming to an end bc his division was sold)

 

THOSE THAT DON’T HAVE IN HOUSE CAFES WANT ONE

 

Nicole

 

SNACK CARTS BREAK MONOTONY

name: Pernod Ricard Innovation Ideas
objective: The purpose of this exercise is to explore how Pernod-Ricard Canada can develop new experiences around J.P. Wiser’s Canadian Whisky, Lot No. 40 Canadian Whisky, Ungava Premium Canadian Gin, Lamb’s Rum, and  Polar Ice Vodka.  Specifically, we'll be exploring how some key consumer trends can fuel that thinking.

name: Hershey Seasonal Celebrations Study
objective:
The objective of this study is to gather feedback from consumers and Influencers on new Hershey visual designs created for seasonal packaging in the U.S. The goal is to gather feedback on whether the new designs reinforce the key equities and character of the Hershey brand, whether they stand out vs. previous designs and how this may help Hershey product make more of a statement that is irresistible to chocolate customers at these key holiday times.

 

  • Hershey’s current seasonal visual language could be more festive

    • “When I think of the visual brand of Hershey packages, I always see brown and silver. Nothing wrong with brown and silver, but, I think maybe during holidays, the packages should “light up” with color and send messages of peace and joy. Three adjectives used to describe the visual language of Hershey’s are: plain, clean, and an oldie, but goody. I think there’s always room for improvement when trying to sell a product. I think Hershey’s is already a “house-hold” brand, but, I think they could strive to create a more fun and creative label - maybe by creating a mascot that’s more appealing to kids.” - Kari P

    • “When I think of Hershey’s, it’s hard for me to think of anything but this familiar branding. It’s very traditional, simple, and recognizable. Perhaps sticking with traditional packaging while incorporating elements of gold for a festive, warm feel.” - Jenn G

    • “The words that describe Hershey’s visual look are simple, a bit plain but clean, iconic bold lettering with brown packaging. For Hershey’s to be more “warm-hearted” during Halloween, I guess I would need to see more specialty bars that are Halloween shaped or designed. Maybe a chocolate pumpkin or bat.” - Marie L

    • “I can't remember anything they've done with the candy bar. It doesn't stand out as a holiday product. The nuggets and miniatures I've seen in holidays selections, but mostly in mixed variety bags with other chocolates. It would be great to see how the product could be more stand alone. Even something as basic as all red letters and green or gold background on their classic design would make a big statement and I think be very impactful! Or a wrapper that looked like a package with ribbon and a tag that had Hershey's name on it. I love candy for the holidays that look fun and special to receive. I could also see a special limited edition flavor like pomegranate that was an annual offering be special!” - Janel C

  • Contributing to charitable causes could help Hershey’s become the “warm-hearted” chocolate brand during holidays

    • Sponsor a charity that everyone could contribute to when you make a Hershey’s seasonal purchase (like sending Kisses to deployed troops.) - Kari P

    • A charitable cause that allows the consumer to feel part of something good and bigger than themselves when they purchase Hershey’s would help them feel warmth toward the brand. Toys for tots would make a great fit. - Jenn G

    • Buy One - Give One

      • To be “warm-hearted” she would expect to see Hershey’s doing giving back campaigns – such as a buy 1 and give 1 campaign where donations are gathered to spread holiday cheer and good will. - Janel C

      • They could become “warm-hearted” by contributing to campaigns that donate to different causes. Even if it’s buy one bag one gets donated. - Maria L

  • They are very passionate about Christmas

    • Favorite of Janel C, Kari P, Jenn G

    • Second favorite of Maria L

  • Halloween is also big

    • Favorite of Marie L, Maria L

    • Second favorite of Janel C, Kari P, Jenn G

  • Everyday life is stressful and busy, the holidays offer a feeling of contentment and relaxation even if they have a lot going on. More time to slow down and enjoy the moments and being with family.

    • Janel C, Kari P, Jenn G, Maria L, Marie L

  • Positive associations with Hershey’s

    • Janel C, Jenn G, Kari P, Maria L, Marie L

  • Many associate Hershey’s with s’mores

    • Janel C, Jenn G, Marie L

  • Hershey’s feels plain and ordinary - but that’s not a bad thing, they can rely on it

    • Janel C, Jenn G

name: Hershey Snacking and Entertainment Study
objective:
The objective of this study is to deeply explore the dynamic of sweet and salty snacking while using electronic devices for fun and relaxation - some actively, some passively. We'll be exploring this usage in granular detail to identify pain and pleasure points of these specific snacking experiences in order to inspire new packaging innovation solutions. How does the packaging of sweet and salty snacks fit into the experience? What are the workarounds for the pain points (messiness, complexity, and general lack of fun-ness and excitement)? What innovation might people be delighted to see?

Snacking and Entertainment Study

name: Hershey's KRAVE Protein Snack Innovation
objective: This study is designed to capture an insightful understanding of what KRAVE stands for amongst three segments:  (i) Enthusiasts (ii) Occasional Users and (iii) Prospects (Healthy Foodies).  Each participant will share their motivations around the KRAVE product and around better-for-snacks in general.  All participants will shop for better-for-you snacks and we'll capture how the experience of how KRAVE exists in those environments.  Amongst KRAVE buyers (Enthusiasts and Occasionals) we'll probe the role that KRAVE currently fulfills.  Amongst everyone, we'll explore where the KRAVE brand could expand into other protein (but non-meat) territories.

name: Deutsch Streetwear/Athleisure Fashion Trends
objective:

Their commentary, video, pictures and screenshots should inspire creative insights for the Deutsch team.

name: Lululemon 2018 Brand Language Study
objective:
The objective of this study is to gather feedback from Guests in several key markets around the world on new core brand language.

Very surprising that people are not familiar with the manifesto - even Current Guests!  But, they like it and it feels very lulu to them.

"Connect" seems to be more appealing to people than "Bond"

Many have noted they feel empowered by the statement Sweat, Grow, Bond/Connect

Some distaste for "Sweat" (Craig D called it "The Moist Life")

Only phrase consistently turning them off in the manifesto is the one about "children being the orgasm of life"

One and Done's are positively influenced by learning about LLL's efforts towards social responsibility and sustainability.  Good ex : Melanie M

name: Deutsch Reebok Fitness/Streetwear/Fashion Study
objective:
The objective of this study is to collect feedback on three distinct positioning territories for Reebok and to more fully understand what currently stokes excitement in 20-25 yr olds within the fitness/streetwear/fashion world and why. Markets included: UK, US, China

- China: "Follow No One" most popular manifesto, with third as backup. Comments reflect increasing attitude of independence (partly a result of single child policy) Over the years, Shanghai’s street-style scene has been a reflection of this, from wild experimentation to a more mature level of style. Shanghai shows sophisticated knowledge of streetwear and fashion brands as athleisure takes off there. China Fashion Bloggers is an aggregator that brings together the best of China’s English-language fashion content (including Zhang’s blog) for a domestic and international audience and displays this attitude. Multiple mentions of Chengdu-born, Beijing-based Fil Xiaobai, who started posting her own street-style snaps on Chinese microblogging platform Weibo. The competition to be photographed is tough and street-style photographers in China, just like in the West, have their favorites.

- UK: majority of inspirational figures and influencers are popular mixed race people (athletes, dancers, designers, actors). Overriding sentiment about Reebok is that they are slightly dated but do one great classic product which is timeless (the Reebok classic trainers). Instagram is HUGE for exposure to brands and personalities. Many use it as a research/discovery tool. Aware of Instagram algorithms that tailor their feeds for advertising (eg advertising brands that their influencers wear). However, this has led some participants leaving Instagram all together as they get frustrated with their impulse buys and mindless scrolling. Streetwear participants frustrated with ‘hypebeast’ and overpriced resale market. It’s turning them off certain brands such as Supreme (a lot of hate for Supreme). Most positive response to 'Follow No One' manifesto. They like the idea of ‘the personal brand’ and saying f*ck you to big brands such as Nike. A lot of people thought that ‘Find Truth’ was cheesy, pretentious and had little relevance for fitness. 

- US: frustrations with resale market driving up streetwear prices, like the UK majority of inspiration comes from mixed raced athetes and celebrities, inspiration comes mostly from Instagram and pop culture, streetwear participants appreciate that streetwear is the intersection of style and comfort, fitness participants appreciate funcational and stylish fitness apparel with performance features. Female participants want more visibility for women in streetwear culture, with more fits and designs geared towards them. They'd even like to see more unisex options vs. the current male centric. They want to see more body positivity and inclusivity in size and styles for both men and women (i.e. not everything HAS to be tight - although many do like to wear tight apparel.) Reebok is respected by many as a player in the streetwear and fitness industries, but some aren't as familiar with Reebok as they are with other brands or they associate it with specific sports like hockey. The terminology 'I train' seems to only apply when they are competing, if they are not working towards a competition more likely to refer to it as 'working out.' First and third manifesto's are testing most positively. The first is most relatable and the third ignites a fire in them.

name: Intermix - Fashion, Shopping and Life
objective:
This study is a deep-dive amongst both High Value Customers (loyalists) and “Ambivalents” to reveal the role Intermix plays in the wardrobe of today’s female contemporary/luxury RTW customer. We want to understand her current discovery and exploration patterns on mobile as well as other sources, and what generates loyalty toward any shopping destination? Amongst current High Value customers, we want to crystallize the Intermix USP. Amongst Ambivalents, we'll look at obstacles preventing them from experiencing the brand, and reasons why lapsed buyers might have moved away. Amongst all, we'll identify opportunities to increase loyalty and meet unmet needs.

General observations across segments

  • Lots of inspiration from everywhere, IG to magazines (for our older ladies), fashion is top-of-mind for them

  • Lots of shopping happening at lots of different places, hunting for sales and deals means hopping from site to site

  • Favorite go-to retailers offer a fab range/edit of brands, styles AND deals, and a good return policy! (lots more returns online than in-store)

  • Sites like Outnet, Barneys Warehouse and of course sales on every site, mean lots of opportunistic shopping and bargain-hunting, not borne of a need, but getting a killer deal

  • The edit is critical - it saves time, but also strengthens the relationship and the feeling the store 'gets' you and knows what you want

  • A personal relationship with sales peeps and stylists only deepen this relationship, serving up suggestions, styling tips, special advance sales, closet refreshes etc.

  • Versatility is huge - fave outfits go the distance, from day to night looking fab

  • In their fave outfits, women feel beautiful and great and sexy but also confident

  • Not everyone loves to shop, for some it feels like a chore

  • Shopping feels stressful to some, online works best for them

  • It can be difficult to find interesting workwear

  • Service is everything! They so appreciate small details that make them feel taken care of like being offered water or champagne

 

Intermix-specific observations across segments

  • Many complaints about in store and online return policy, especially for on-sale pieces (which are all final sale)

  • Sales associates are helpful

  • Complaints about lack of store locations and inconsistency between stores. Some better than others. Some store closures

  • Many want nicer dressing rooms

  • Inconsistency with sales associates

  • The Intermix woman reflects cool, sexy, interesting etc.

  • There seems to be a disconnect between the online and in-store experience

 

High Value Participants

  • Love the variety they can find at Intermix - everyday outfits to special occasions

  • Sense of discovery in store - many have a “person” they love that they can rely on to pull pieces they may not have thought of but end up loving

  • Some like that the brands are mixed so it’s easy to mix and match

 

Ambivalents

  • Some feel too old for Intermix

  • Can feel intimidated by Intermix’s small sizing

    • One is intimidated by Intermix (website) because she feels they only have size 2 models...she says it seems like its for skinny girls (she's a size 4-6). Seems like it’s important to her to see herself in the clothes by having relatable models. She said the SA was helpful with size, but when she ordered a dress from online it ran small

name: Hershey - Impulse Snacking Choices & Behavior
objective:
The objective of this study is to better understand the dynamics of “front-end” snack choices – ie the types of packaged snacks people pick up on impulse before exiting a store. We'll explore primary contenders and what drives choice among them, how the consideration sets vary by consumer and day part, mindset and mood surrounding purchases and consumption experience to reveal unmet needs.

KEY DRIVERS OF SELECTION:

- price/promo

- protein content (helps them justify their choices, vaguely feels healthier)

- flavor craving (ie i need peanut butter or chocolate or something spicy)

- habit (ie stop at Speedway every morning at same time and get same thing or narrow range of things)

- frame of mind (ie just worked out so I want a healthier snack)

- healthy equivalents of familiar favorites (ie granola peanut butter cups rather than Reese's)

- new flavors of familiar favorites (PayDay bites)

- stocking up ("work snacks" or gums/mints)

- unusual or new items - either for themselves or for someone they know (ie mint chocolate is my dad's fav flavor so I got him Hershey's Cookie Layer Crunch)

- childhood memories/nostalgia

Ex. of emotional power of impulse snacks: Just wanted to share. I thought this was so nice to read/listen to as well as what I have seen the reason being why people gravitate towards certain snacks, happy memories "But as I was eating my mike and ikes, I actually had a very happy memory from grad school recently lost a friend of mine who was in grad school with me, great guy named Dan, And I remember the many nights that we would buy these jumbo bags of Mike and ikes and hot tamales, and we would just pass them back and forth in our classroom.  We had about twenty eight of us in grad school at the same time that were also working full time and going to school full time at Carnegie Mellon.  And as I was sitting there eating my Mike and Ike's . It made me think of Dan, who we lost just about two and a half three weeks ago.  So, um, it's funny how something as simple as a single serve a single serve box of candy can spark those memories for you. " (Lisa M)

 

Front-End Snacks v. Snacks in the Pantry at Home:  Snacks at home tend to be somewhat healthier, pragmatic. Front-End snacks are emotionally-driven (lizard brain) purchases

 

-Some mentioned frustration of "single serving" snacks not truly being one serving. They'd like to see single portions or resealable packaging.

name: Lululemon Run Collective Study
objective: The objective of this research is to engage with serious Runners (identified by lululemon) on how they choose their gear, what product attributes drive their choices, what they think of lululemon as a brand - and a brand for running, and what they would love to see lululemon develop in its future run product designs.

name: Harvest Health & Recreation Cannabis Retail Purchases
objective:
The objective of this study is to uncover unmet consumer needs in the current cannabis retail industry (in AZ), so that Harvest Health & Recreation can enhance their overall customer experience. We'll explore the opinions of those who are purchasing from competitive retailers, as well as those who've purchased from Harvest in the past but have not returned. We'll explore opportunities for both purchasing and product development.

APPS are popular to stay in the know and comparison shop - WeedMap, Leafly.  Younger buyers are also sharing their choices of product and retailer on Instagram

Social Media Huge Opportunity to bump up!  More engagement with their own consumer.

Price promos are pretty important - BoGo (buy one get one) is pretty common but LOCATION/CONVENIENCE drives most decisions.  Coupons by mail and follow-up messaging by text seems effective.

Scent important in choosing strain of flower - flower is a great experience but vape/cartridges are purchased most often for discretion and portability. Shatter/dabs are choice for strong potency. Edibles are more for fun, when the effect is less urgent

Among lapsed, Harvest is getting low marks for customer service and sometimes (depending on location) a not-great atmosphere (cramped, like a bank, etc).  There is also a lot of new competition so people are simply finding more convenient, closer locations

Many are frustrated by long wait times due to lack of staff/budtenders. Experienced purchasers are frustrated by new purchasers "clogging" lines. They're looking for quick and easy, express purchasing, wishing for pre-order/more delivery options.

INNOVATION IDEAS:

- Message is not getting through about Harvest's programs to inform - invest in more publicity?  There is a lot of desire to learn more about product benefits, new products, etc - what education can they offer, voice of thought leadership, etc

- Advertise delivery where it exists - these people want convenience

- Could budtenders develop personal relationships with customers (the way text relationships are evolving at high-end fashion retail)? People would love the intimacy of personal texting. They want highly personalized service

- People want a loyalty program. They are price comparing a lot so financial incentives seem to be powerful. Also, people want to settle into a relationship where they trust the source.

-There's a large desire for education (classes, workshops, etc.)

name: Lululemon 2019 Sweat Life Language Study
objective: The objective of this study is to gather feedback from both Core and "Ambivalent" Guests on articulations of "The Sweat Life", in order to find the language that best communicates the idea.

name: Lululemon Men's Casual and Swim Shorts Study
objective:
The objective of this study is to collect insights on the men’s casual short and swim categories – ie drivers of purchase, unmet needs, role in wardrobe, attributes that drive purchase (where it hits the knee, keeping cool, aesthetic that looks good/fits in), replenishment dynamics, etc. to uncover why men who have purchased some sort of pant/athletic short from lulu have not moved on to swim products or casual shorts and test hypothesis that there may be an “amphibious” product need for casual shorts that are quick dry (can be swum in).

Observations on Swim Shorts

Swim shorts that can be appropriate for other activities (like going out to lunch) are appealing

Boardshorts are outdated, some prefer shorter ‘Euro length’ length of swim shorts vs. longer board shorts (one avoids especially when traveling because they look too “American”)

It’s common for men to only have 1-2 pairs of swim shorts

Many only replenish their swim shorts every few years (especially if they live in a colder climate, feels like a waste of money to spend on new swim shorts)

Many were unaware that lululemon offered swim shorts

Some were disappointed in lack of swimwear options in lululemon’s store, some found them harder to locate than

Many also want pockets in swim shorts, but some don’t because they’re worried about jumping into the water with their phone/wallet in their pocket so could be important to offer both

 

Observations on Casual Shorts

Some find a style and stock up on multiple colors/patterns

Many have a preference for shorts that hit above the knee

Four pockets seem to be a must

There are occasions where they would love to wear shorts to work but it’s not ‘appropriate’ or allowed (like to work, out to dinner, to weddings, etc.)

Some disappointment in the lack of selection for sizes/colors/fits of lululemon casual shorts in store

 

Additional Observations

Strong opinions on liners in or not in shorts and/ or bathing suits

Several mentions of associating non-athletic LLL apparel with golf/golfing

Getting them to try on a short or swim short from LLL almost always has a positive reaction if not purchase now they state they will in the future

Lots of interest in a versatile short that can double as swim

Many chose to try on swim/casual shorts that are similar to things they already own so they’d fit seamlessly into wardrobe

name: Lululemon Accessories
objective: To identify their unmet accessories needs across “Sweat accessories”, “Bags”, and “Overall SweatLife accessories”. name: Tiffany & Co. Luxury Gift Packaging
objective:
Tiffany & Co. has determined that their customer’s experience of receiving merchandise via e-commerce can be improved with mindful innovation around the designed elements of boxing, wrapping and gift wrapping. This study will explore that experience, sharing several prototype options with various key Tiffany & Co. segments. The resulting insights will be used to help guide choices for executing against the new packaging strategy for launch later in 2019.

FEEDBACK ON BOX A

Loved. On brand and luxurious. But did not notice some elements in the package (return slip, shopping bag, etc.) And did not seem interested in the removable internal structure. (Claudia R / Sophisticate / Silver / Tiffany customer)

Loved immediate presentation and that the item was the focal point right on top in classic blue box. Branding made it feel luxurious. Items were secure. Loved pull tab for collateral. Beautiful wrapping, loved bag included for gifting. Only concern was if box got wet there was no protection between cardboard and item. Had some difficulty ripping pre-cut tab open. Would have loved to see cleaning cloth included. (Lauren S / Ascender / Gold)

Felt like opening a present. “9” Color-blocked white and blue feels modern and luxurious. name: Terez - Activewear & Loungewear Study
objective:
This study will delve deeply into the everyday lives of women buying premium leggings. We'll look at her go-to outfits and what she is looking for with these key occasions (ie comfort, versatility, working out, being on-trend, self-expression, etc). We'll explore what role leggings play in her overall wardrobe and what drives her discovery of new looks and new brands. What factors drive her choices when it comes to leggings? How do the lines fall between comfort, fitness-specific benefits, and fashion (and where are these lines blurred)? What product traits (if any) trump price sensitivity? Finally, what can we learn from her lifestyle that could inform and inspire new product opportunities? We'll be listening closely to identify differences between the age segments.

Ex. of comments:

Appears to be increasing interest in matching pieces for activewear (Janine, Paula)

"Comfy but cute" is the vernacular we are hearing a LOT for weekend wear

Comfy fashiony graphic T's to go under jackets could be opp for Terez (joy, female empowered messages to reinforce brand voice)

Lines are even blurring between activewear/loungewear and casual wear in the sense that everyone wants soft, comfy, fabrics with some stretch that don't wrinkle

When women find activewear pieces they love they buy in multiples (Ariana, Lauren T)

name: Tiffany In-Store Merchandising Study
objective:
Tiffany & Co. hypothesizes that the brand can strengthen brand desirability, grow trends and AUR faster than the average network store by implementing an in-store presentation and consumer experience that surprises and delights.  A cross-functional team has been assembled to pilot test to prove/disprove this hypothesis. 

The purpose of this mobile ethnography study is to collect insights around the following points, as customers’ perceptions should be stimulated by the new store concept:

Desirability – How can Tiffany become a brand she desires to wear herself?
Relevancy – How can Tiffany be a part of her world, and a brand worn and talked about in her circle?
Exclusivity – How can Tiffany Jewelry be perceived as exclusive and worn only by people in her world/her tribe?

“Test stores” as well as “Control Stores” have been designated to assess the effectiveness of these hypotheses.

East/north campus consists of business, engineering, math, & natural science majors. South campus consists of arts & humanities, health sciences, and social science majors. I have only been to the dining hall on north campus once, but I remember it being a lot bigger than south campus. However, I do follow UML Dining on instagram & have noticed that this semester north/east made a lot more changes/upgrades to their dining hall and not ours. For example, they have a pasta station, bread station, & make-your-one trail mix station. Other than the improvements, I think that the dining halls offer similar meals. In addition to their dining hall, though, they have a place called “Hawks Nest” on east campus that has smoothies, which is not offered anywhere else. East campus is a residential campus, while all of those students attend class on north campus, which is an academic campus. Generally, students think of those campuses as one. (Hannah)

 

On why she goes to Dunkin for breakfast sandwiches: "The dining halls would not be as convenient because they don’t like us taking food out of the dining halls and therefore would have packaging or bags to carry them to class" - ie she wants it on the go (Emily M)

name: Google P&E - Olders
objective:
Google’s Platform & Ecosystems Brand has conducted global quantitative research to understand Olders (50-75) vs. gen pop, and have uncovered a number of interesting insights about Olders on a psychographic level.
Building on these insights, our objective in this P&E-focused qual is to understand how they choose and use
brands— especially tech brands like Google, with a spotlight on Google P&E categories (smartphones, wireless carriers, computing, digital experiences) and brands (Android & Comms apps [Messages, Phone/Dialer, Google Duo, Contacts], Google Fi, Chromebook, Google Play, Chrome Browser). This work can help Google shape the products they build and the stories and marketing strategies they use to connect.

name: Making Choices in the World of Luxury Makeup
objective:
Issues of diversity, race, and inclusion have come to the forefront of the social landscape in the US. While CHANEL has been focused on the degree to which CHANEL's beauty products (makeup, skincare) are viewed as inclusive, the increased importance placed on this topic by consumers compels CHANEL to understand the subject more deeply.

Across brand perceptions, communications, and product, CHANEL would like to understand the factors that lead to a brand being viewed as inclusive, as well as how CHANEL performs in these areas versus competitors.

name: ペットフードに関する調査
objective:
この度はZIWI（ジウィ）に関する調査にご参加いただきありがとうございます！お忙しい中、ご自身についての情報など事前に共有いただきありがとうございました。

今回は、リサーチを通してみなさまのご意見をお聞かせいただけましたら幸いです。初めに、ご自身のペットフードに対する考え方や、実際にZIWIを手に触れたうえでの使い勝手や感想などについて率直に教えていただければと思います。回答に正解・不正解はありませんので、自由にお答えいただければと思います。  

いただいた回答をよりよく理解するためにも、写真や動画も可能な限りアップしていただけると助かります。みなさまの体感を限りなくリアルに知ることが今回のリサーチの目的です。今回のリサーチでは質問がLookLookサイト上にアップされますので、そこからご都合に合わせて回答をいただければと思います。

掲載される質問につきましては、下記期間内にご回答いただけますようお願いいたします。

  • トピック１：８月１３日（金）

  • トピック２：８月１４日（土）〜２４日（火）

  • トピック３：８月１９日（木）まで

  • トピック４：８月２２日（日）まで

  • トピック５：８月２６日（木）

みなさまからのご回答を拝見するのを楽しみにしております！
